### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:What could you add a line to? Choices:  A: bus stop B: graph C: post office D: grass E: play<n>Output:		grass<n><n>###  Solution 1: Greetings from 🅦︎<n>I have written a recursive function and I have tried it on the test cases. It does give correct answer for all test cases. It runs time O(N*N) where N is the maximum number of nodes in the graph. <n>```<n># Functions<n><n>def hasPath(node,parent,visited,result):<n>    if node == parent:<n>        return True<n><n>    if parent == visited[0]: #find the first node which was visited<n>        return result!= [ ]<n><n>    if node in result:  #check if path exists<n>        return True<n>    if node in visited:  #do not go back to a visited node<n>        return False<n>    if not hasPath(node, node, visited, result):<n>        return False<n>    <n><n><n><n><n>#Driver Program<n><n>n = int(input())<n>graph = []<n>for i in range(n):<n>    parent = ''<n>    visited = []<n>    while True:<n>        node = input()<n>        if node == 'M':<n>            break<n>        <n>        newNode = node<n>        if parent == 'X':<n>            newNode = node + 'X'<n>        if not newNode[2:] in graph:<n>            graph.append(newNode)<n>        current = parent<n>        visited.append(current)<n>        print(current)<n>        if hasPath(newNode,parent,visited):<n>            res = hasPath(newNode,'X',visited)<n>            result = visited<n>            parent = newNode<n>   <n>            print(res)<n>result = hasPath('X','Y',visited)<n>print(result)<n><n>```

Put it in a box<n><n>Input: One morning, an overworked professor stood before his entire class and made an announcement. "Liberty means," he began, "the absence of any restraint on liberty. Liberty means equal opportunity for all in the exercise and enjoyment of the rights of life, liberty, and property." Unfortunately, he didn't think to define his terms, and so the class got to work asserting and defending the following rights: the right to ride the unicycle, the right to ride the bicycle, and the right to walk. A dispute arose, however, when some students insisted that one person should be allowed to monopolize all three, but when the class voted (76 in favor and 54 against), the matter was settled. That afternoon, the same professor began his next lecture by announcing his intention to define his terms. He said, "In pursuit of liberty it is necessary," he exclaimed, "to subdue our desires and keep our selfishness under control." Unfortunately, again he failed to define his terms. When, therefore, the students made the following rights for themselves: the right of the rich to vote, the right of the whites to own property, and the right of the Protestants to vote, the professor decided that if his students could define their own terms, surely he could too. That afternoon, he told his class, "These are the definitions of liberty, justice, freedom, property, and equality, which I have formulated. They are as follows: * Liberty = that which is exercised by one person on his own behalf, and that which is exercised on behalf of another. * Justice = that which is in accordance with established laws. * Freedom = that which is determined by established laws. * Property = that which is not in accordance with established law. * Equality = that which is determined without established laws." The students then began to defend their prior rights, but they no longer could. When the professor asked them how the rich could vote but the poor could not, they couldn't answer. They realized that the rich are allowed to vote because certain laws make it so.  The professor

The shamrock sails into the harbor using the first coordinate of the function d = 1/(s^9/S) + 1/(s^20/S) to maintain a constant speed S m per minute. A wind of constant force F blows straight out at 99deg and a 23deg angle from the y-axis. The winds do not sway the sailboat or shamrock. The dock at s = 70 ft is the point where the boat hits. After the sailboat and shamrock hit the dock, a 10 ft fishing boat with the x distance of g = 1/(2 s^6) + 1/(2 s^(35/6)) travels at a steady state rate of d = 1/(15/s^5) + 1/(15 s^(63/13)). Choices:  A: cupboard B: countertop C: water D: hardware department E: england<n>Output:		(C) Water<n><n>### Methodology:<n><n>Method used:<n><n>Explanation:<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>How many students are  in the math department at this large university? The answer is 36. Let’s see how we determine the value of a and b.<n><n>If we assume a=36 and b=26, then a+b-1 would equal 67. Then we know that a+b-1=67. Then what is one less than a+b-1? Well, that is an even number, so we should divide it by 2, which would equal 7, and that number is one less than a and one less than b. So we now know that a + b - a + b = 7.<n><n>Then we know that by subtracting a from both sides of the equation, which equals 7. And we know a=36, so then 36-7=29. Similarly, we know b-7=19, which means b = 26.<n><n>### Instructions: Answer the questions with your own thoughts. Do not use the help menu in MS-Word.<n><n>What is the smallest three digit number we can form using no digit greater than 3?<n><n>Explanation <n>First, we will subtract 0 from each of the digits, because 0 is a possible number that we can create in our digit and it will make it easier to create the perfect number. Next, we will subtract 1 from each of the digits to create the perfect number that is between 26 and 29.<n><n>Next, we will make each of the digits have a number greater than 1 and 3 and we will subtract 1 at a time to create the digits. Finally, we will remove all the 2 digits and add the numbers together to create 135.<n><n>### Tutorial:<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:What is the opposite of a village? Choices:  A: rural area B: africa C: ohio D: big city E: tribe<n>Output:		 A<n><n>(a) 90 minus 5, plus 20 plus 40 equals 90, so there are 55 doberman puppies. (b) The toothbrushes total 330. She gave away 53 in January, leaving a total of 277. She gave away 67 in February, leaving 210. In March, she gave away 46, leaving 164. In April, she gave away half of that, leaving 82. In May, she gave away the other half, 41.   So, in April and May, she gave away 93 more toothbrushs than in February. (c) Sally picks 10 less each day (on Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday) than in the previous day, so we need 30 - 10 - 10 + 30 + 10 = 30 seashellers per day. On Thursday, she picksed 30 - 5 = 25, so on Friday she picked 30 - 25 = 5. She can make $1.20 * 30 = $36 when she sells all of the seashells on Friday. (d) On the way back to the shore, they caught half of the fish remaining in the boat. So, they still have 18 fish. (e) This may be the greatest question asked yet. "Village" is a noun, the opposite of a noun is a verb, and a noun is either in Africa or in Ohio - just one of many, many wrong answers.

Animals1.new(animal_days.flatten).to_s<n>  <n>  days = n<n>  if Animal.number_of_animals_array.include? n<n>  <n>  <n>  return day_of += [day_of.flatten + day_of_animal]<n>  <n>  else<n>   days_of_animals.select(&:include? day_of).uniq.length,<n>  end<n>  <n>  <n>end #end of find_days<n><n>day

He begged the sheriff to let him get out of the storm. The sheriff said he must kill the cowboy to save himself and escape the storm.  The sheriff said, "I’m not shooting you if you shoot me first."   He told the cowboy it was up to him, and the cowboy said, "This is an easy decision to me.  I will just give up my gun first."   The cowboy handed the sheriff his gun, which the sheriff took from him.   The cowboy then said "you can trust me.  I will give you my horse, too, if you let me live by your law."  The cowboy then gave him his horse.   The sheriff saw it, and he said, "I’ll be damned!  You made the right decision!"   What did the cowboy do next?<n>Output: He killed the sheriff<n>

Choices:  A: advisory B: mandate C: soap opera D: elective E: optional<n>Output:		C: soap opera<n><n>Output: E: optional<n><n>#### Instruction:Given a list of expressions (strings or vectors), write a sequence that evaluates those expressions in order, and outputs a unique sequence of strings, representing the results of evaluation.<n><n>Input: Output of (a + b) (a - b)<n>Output: b<n><n>Input: Outputs of (+ 10) (+ 5) 10 9 4<n>Output: {19 15 24 26}<n><n>Input: Output = (3 - a), a = 2, Output = (3 - 2)= 1<n><n>Input: Output is (5 + 2) / (3 - 2), Output = 28 / 0 = NaN<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>I have asked you to use the [OpenSSL Shell](http://www.openssl-sh.com/) as your coding environment for this assignment.  You have several options for installing OpenSSL on your system, but if you do not have OpenSSL on your system after installing OpenSSL Shell, you can install it on Linux and Mac OS X systems and some Unix distributions by simply typing:<n><n>```<n>$ sudo easy_install openssl<n>```<n>* or<n><n>```<n>$ easy_install openssl <n>``` <n><n>Alternatively, on Linux or Mac OS X, type<n><n>```<n>$ wget http://www.openssl.org/source/openssl-0.9.8l-23.tar.gz   <n>$ tar zxvf openssl-0.98l-23-src.tar.gz <n>$ cd openssl-0.8.8l-22/i686-pc-linux-gnu/<n>$./Configure <n>$ make <n>$ make install<n>```<n><n>*or* <n><n>```<n>$./Configure -openssldir=`pwd`/lib/crypto <n>$ make<n>$ make install <n>```<n><n>The reason we do NOT want to run: `sudo easy_install openssl` is that a) many students do not use this system and b) the make install command may override the environment. That is why we tell you to install openssl on your system if you do not have it.<n><n><n># Task

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where are people likely to find food? Choices:  A: opera B: supermarket C: building D: conference E: apartment<n>Output:		A<n><n>### Constraints<n>* Time limit of 3 min<n><n>### Additional<n>Informally:<n>This is a math related question on finding a difference. 5<n><n>#### Solution<n><n>##### Solution<n>    #include<bits/stdc++.h><n>    using namespace std;<n>    string s,t;<n>    vector<int> arr,c;<n>    map<int,int> id;<n><n>    int main()<n>    {<n>        cin >> s >> t;<n>        for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++)<n>        {<n>            if(i ==s.size()-1)<n>            {<n>                id[s[i]]++;<n>            }else<n>            {<n>                auto p = find(id.begin(),id.end(),s[i]);<n>                if(p!=id.end())<n>                {<n>                    id[p->second]+=1;<n>                }else<n>                {<n>                   id[s[i]].reset();<n>                   id[t[i]].reset(1);<n>                }<n>            }<n>            arr.push_back(id[s[i]]);<n>        }<n>        for(int j=0;j<t.size();j++)<n>        {<n>           for(int k=0;k<t.size();k++)<n>           {<n>                for(int i=j;i!=k;i++)<n>                {<n>                 if(arr[i]==arr[i+1])<n>                  if(id[arr[i]]!=id[arr[i+1]])<n>                  {<n>                    if(arr[i]+1==arr[i+2])<n>                      c.push_back(arr[i+1]);<n>                    else<n>                      c.insert(c.end(),arr[i]+1);<n>                  }<n>                 id[arr[i]].reset();<n>                  id[arr[i+2]].reset();<n>                }<n>                id[t[j]].reset(1);<n>                id[t[(j+t.size())-1]].reset(1)<n>           }<n>        }<n>        cout<<arr.size()+1;<n><n>    }<n><n>To Run :<n><n>g++

If the farmer owned more sheep at first, what is the total number of sheep he owned after the sheep were sheared? Choices: 3A: 42 B: 23 C: 32 D: 27 E: 33<n>Output: B<n><n><n>## Instruction: Input the answer with integer values<n><n><n><n><n>```py<n><n><n><n><n>input = int(input())<n><n><n><n>inputDict = {<n>    0: ["not an int"]*, 1: ["a bit too much"]*, 2: ["a bit less"]*, 3: ["meh"]*, 4: ["good"]*<n>}<n><n><n><n><n>print(inputDict[input])<n><n>```<n>

Choices:  A: cause death B: cause bleeding C: falling down D: become infected E: claim insurance<n>Output:		(A) Cause death<n><n>### Instruction:<n>Input: Five less...<n>### Solution:<n>```python<n>def solution():<n><n>    def process(x):<n>        return str(x)<n>    n_Doberman = int(input(f"Enter the number of Dobermans: "))<n>    n_Doberman_Puppies = (n_Doberman // 3) * 3<n>    n_other = n_Doberman - n_Doberman + n_Doberman * 2<n>    <n>    for i in range(n_Doberman_puppies, 0, -1):<n>        if i >= n_Doberman:<n>            return 0<n>    print(f"The number of Schnauzer Puplies: {i}")<n>    if i <= n_other:<n>        return 0<n>                <n>def solution_2():<n><n>    def first_part(x):<n>        x = int(x)<n>        s = 0<n>        for i in range(x):<n>            s += 5-3*i<n>        return s<n>    def second_part(x): #1<n>        return s<n>        <n>    def second_two_part(x):#2<n>        y = 1<n>        m_x = x<n>        while x > 0:<n>          y = 1<n>          m_x = x // y<n>          x = x - m_x * y<n>          for i in range(m_x // 3, 0, - 1):<n>              y += 3<n>              m_x = m_x - y<n>        <n>        return y<n>            <n>    def third_part(x): <n>        z = x<n>        for i in  range(z):<n>            z += 1<n>        return z<n><n><n><n>    n = int(input(("Enter a number: ")))<n>    print("First Part = ", first_part(n))<n>    print("Second Part  = ", second_part(n))    <n>    print("Second Two Part  = ", second2_part(n)) <n>    print("Third Part  = ", third_part(n))     <n><n>def solution_3():<n>    def print_data(n, x):<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:In what place could you find air that has been breathed by only a few people recently? Choices:  A: train station B: house C: cupboard D: cricket stadium E: surface of earth<n>Output:		E: surface of earth. - The only place that would have the same air as another place is the Earth.<n><n>## Solution<n><n>* <n>```swift<n>class Solutions {<n>    init(number: Int, month: Month) {<n>        self.number = number<n>        self.month = month<n>    }<n>}<n>struct Month {<n>    <n>    case January<n>    case February<n>}<n>var number = 0<n>var month = Month.January<n>var countDay = 0<n><n>func getNewIndex(index: Int) -> Int {<n>    return (index + 1) % 5<n>} <n>func getLastIndex(index: Int, step: Int) -> Int? {<n>    let lastIndex = index + step<n>    if (50 < lastIndex) {<n>        lastIndex = 0<n>    }<n>    return lastIndex<n>}<n><n>class Solution {<n>    var newSol = [Solutions]();<n>    var tempSol = [Solutions];<n><n>    var currentDayIndex = 6<n>    var sum = 0<n>    var index = 0<n>    func initSum() -> Int {<n>        if (0 < index && index < 5) {<n>            let sol : Solutions = Solutions(number: number, month: month) <n>            sum += sol.sumOfTotalNumOfBeds()<n>            sum += sol.sumOfTotalDay()<n>            newSol.append(sol)<n>            index += 1<n>            if (50 < (currentDayIndex + 1)) {<n>                index = 0<n>                currentDayIndex = 0<n>            }<n>            tempSol = [Solution]()<n>        }<n>        if (sum == 0) {<n>            index = 0<n>            sum = 1<n>        }<n>        currentDayIndex += 1<n>        index += 1<n>        return sum<n>    }<n>}

Choices:  A: allergic reaction B: gain weight C: have fun D: heartburn E: food poisoning<n>Output:		 E<n><n>#### Multiple  Choice Question - 1<n><n>```py<n>def main():<n>    n = int(input())<n>    s = input()<n>    arr = list(map(int, s.split())<n>    for x in range(len(arr)):<n>        for i in range(len(s)):<n>            if x >= len(s) or x < 0 or s[i] == arr[x]:<n>                if arr[x] % 2 == 0:<n>                    break<n>                else:<n>                    pass<n>    print(arr[x - 1])<n>main()<n>```<n><n>#### Multiple 2 Choice Question - 2<n>```py<n>def solve(n, m):<n>    ans = [1]<n>    for i in range(n, m // 2 + 1):<n>        ans.append(ans[-1] + 1)<n>    ans.append(ans[n - 1] + m)<n>    return ans<n><n>print(solve(36, 11))<n>```<n><n>#### Multiple 3 Choice Question - 3<n>```py<n>def n_sum(n,m):<n>    sum = 0<n>    for i in [5, 1, 1]:<n>        sum = sum + int(i)<n>    return sum<n>    # if sum in [0,1]:<n>    #     return sum // 2<n>    # return ""<n><n>n = int(input())m = int(input()) print(n_sum(n-1, m) - \<n>n_sum(n, m+1))<n>```<n>#### Multiple 4 Choice Question - 4<n>```<n>def main(m, n, sum):<n>    m +=1<n>    result = sum<n>    for i in ranges(1, m):<n>        result = result + ranges(1, n + 1)<n>        ans = result // 2<n>        if ans == "":<n>            return ans<n>        m += 1<n><n>main(3, 3, 12)<n>```<n><n>### Links with Resources:<n>* [Examples to solve](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/algorithms/arrays-and-strings/dynamic-programming/index.html)<n>*

He eats three beans and two grains of rice for a total cost of $14. He receives a 20% discount on the total cost. What does the man pay?<n>Output:  $11.20<n><br>The man's cost is $14.00 initially. There are five ways to arrive at that total price with three beans and two rice; three beans, one bean, two beans (three different combinations), two beans, two rice, four rice, two rice, one grain (two different combinations), two rice, one grains (one way), four rice, one grain and two rice. So what the man really pays is: $((14/100) * 5* 14) + (14/10) * $10+ (14/12) * 3 + $9 + $6 + $2.50 + $13.50.<n><br>The sum is then $(140/120) * 14; $11.25<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Having your marijuana in bags help keep it what? Choices:  A: entertainment B: neat C: happy D: intoxicating E: illegal<n>Output:		A<n><n>#!/usr/bin/python<n><n>"""Programming Tutorial - 19: How did programming help a certain city? - Multiple Choice"""<n><n># Code<n>class MultipleChoice:<n><n>    def __init__(self):<n>        self.num_correct = 0<n><n>    def num_answered(self) -> int:<n>        return len(self.answers)<n><n>    def __str__(self):<n>        print(self.answers, self.correct)<n><n>    def add(self, *args) -> int:<n><n>        for ans, correct in args:<n>            self.answers.append(ans)<n>            self.correct.append(correct)<n>        self.correct = [True, False] + self.correct<n><n>    def format_data(self) -> str:<n>        """<n>        Returns a string with formatted data, ready to be displayed to the user.<n><n>        Args: NONE<n>        """<n><n>        return ''.join(['  '.join([(char for char in correct if char is True), \<n>    (char for char in ans if char is True)]) for answer, correct in zip(self.answers[:], self.correct[:])]) + '\n'<n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    ans = [input(), input(), input(), input()]<n>    print(MultipleChoice().format_data())<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where would you buy a ticket to sit in a room with a lot of chairs facing the same direction? Choices:  A: conference B: theater C: building D: floor E: church<n>Output:		Church<n><n>#### Explanation:<n><n>Let 20 = # of Doberman pups<n>then  <n>    5 < 20 + 20 - 20<n>       5 < 40 – 0<n>       5 <(26) - 0<n>       5< 10<n>        -4 < 5       <n>       4 > -4<n>        8 > 0 <n>       8 >4<n>        12/6<n>        2<n><n><n>input:<n>    Sally picks 20 seashells on monday<n>    On Tuesday, Sally picks half as many as she did<n>    Sally sells each for $1.2   <n>                  <n>    Then we can write<n>    $20*20*1.2*0.5 = $54<n>                       <n>    which can be converted to<n>    $10*0.25 = $2.50<n><n>    Let 4 = Jordan's catch<n>    Since 4 double what Jordan catch<n>    $2.50 + $2.50 = 6.50 - 4 = 2.50<n>    After tipping over they now have<n>    2.50 = remaining fish<n><n><n>let 41=room #<n><n><n><n>let church be the room where church faces the congregation<n>                   <n><n><n><n><n><img src=http://blog.g2crowd.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/G2Crowd-104_1024x414.jpg<n><n><n><n><n>#### Solution<n><n>## Reasoning:<n><n>1) We can apply the distributive property to get<n><n>$5 < 20+20-20<n>$5 < 40 -0 <n>$5 < (26) -0<n>$5 < (10)<n><n>$4 >1<n>$51 > 4<n>$\frac{12}{6}$ > 1<n>$\frac{10}{6} $ > $\frac{12}{4}$ : <n>$\frac{20}{12} $ >$\frac{12 }{4}$<n><n><n><n>2) $40*0.80 = 40

Choices:  A: ghost town B: third world country C: human body D: rug E: hospital<n>Output:		D <n><n>Input: If a train leaves Seattle at 7:05pm heading south with a speed of 85 mph what time will it be in Los Angeles?<n>Output: Los Angeles time: 1:30pm<n><n>### Constraints<n>* The input length is up to 100 characters.<n>* The output length is 1 (exact number).<n><n>### Notes<n>* When you can, do try to use code/computational thinking to solve the problem.<n>* Remember to answer in code.<n><n>## 입력<n><n>```<n>Five less than three times the n\<n>umber of Doberman dobers are 91.\<n>If the number of Dobermans doges is 20 55\<n>how many Schnauzr Schnauzes are there 55.<n>```<n><n>## 출력<n><n>코드로 답글해주세요<n><n>## 방법<n><n>몽키파이터로 문제를 해결하면 되나요?<n><n>## 풀이 (코드)<n><n>```python<n>#1<n># 몬키패더 5개로 해결해요<n><n>import re<n><n># 입데이터 변수나 튜플 입넷<n>n=3<n>three=n*2<n>d=3*n/two<n>if n-d==3:<n>    print("yes it is equal")<n>else:<n>    print("no it is not equal")<n><n># 워크 투플 만들기<n>n=int(input('enter a number\n'))<n>d=n-4<n>sum=n<n>if d>2:<n>    d=d-2<n>    sum=sum-d<n>if sum==1:<n>    print(sum)<n>else:<n>    d=(n+1)/2<n>    sum=(n+1)<n>    print(sum-d)<n><n># 코루테로 주어

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where would you hear a viola along side many other string and brass instruments? Choices:  A: symphony B: band C: create music D: orchestra E: string quartet<n>Output:		Symphony<n>### Challenge Question(You only need to answer this for the first problem)<n>- How can you count the number of times the string "times" appears in the sentence and print its position in the sentence if it appears. For example, the string "times" appeared 3 times in the sentence "Ten times the number of times the number of times you divide by the number of x-es in xi equals nine will be the number of times the times you divide by x-es" and its indices were positions 1, 31 and 68 respectively.<n><n>### Solution<n>* 3. I have one index array and it contains the position that the string "times" occur.<n>```python<n>def find_times(S):<n>	times = 0<n>	times_ind = [None]<n>	for character in S: # Loop through each character <n>		if character.isdigit(): # Skip the characters that are not the index that the letter is in <n>			continue <n>		else:<n>			start_pos = times_ind.index(None)<n>			times_ind.insert(start_pos+1,times_ind.pop(start_pos))<n>			while character.islower(): # Skip lowercase vowels (a, e, i, o, u)<n>				ch = character<n>				character += 1<n>				if character.digit():<n>					break<n>			else: <n>				break # I've reached my end character now<n>				<n>			# Find position of the character. <n>			# Check only once as we know it is only 1 digit <n>			print(times_ind.index(ch)) # The print is here so I can check my value and make sure it is what I want it to be(print() is useless in terms of checking values <n>			times += 1 # I've added 1 to the index array above so that that will print 3 when I run it<n>				  # It means that I passed 3 times with the string "times" <n>		return character<n>```<n>And it works on this sentence where the string "times" can be found 3

The conditions are:<n>x &gt; 20 &amp; = 90<n>47 - 20 =  20<n>We know that the 2 conditions hold when x = 20 and y = 25 47 + 20 = 67<n>We can write this in a new linear equation:<n>2x + 25 + 20 + 47 + 67<n>x = -47<n>x &lt; 20 &gt; 90<n>-47 &lt; 25 4-47<n>= 243<n>-y = 25<n>= 2 -y = 25 -243<n>= -218 <n>So, 20 is the number of Dobermam puppies.<n><n>2.	The first month (Jan) is 53, the second month (Feb) is 67, so we know at the end of the 4 months we will divide the remaining count by 4 to account for the missing dooberman<n><n>So if we multiply the number of remaining by 4 we subtract 4 from the number of remaining we know the answer will be 36<n><n>3.	We know the condition<n>x + y = 54<n><n>We subtract 54 from both sides of the equation to get y = 500<n>Then 500 + x = 144<n>Since we know that x is at least 500 we can then subtract x from each side which simplifies our inequality<n>144-500 = -356<n>144-x = -356 which is represented as x + 120 - (356 +120)<n><n>x + y = (646 - 478)<n>= x+268<n>which simplifies to (30 -27)<n>y = 30-27<n>So from our first equation we know that x = 20 but y = 3<n><n>Finally, we take away the fish at our boat to get the remaining number. Since y = 3

Your job is to calculate the difference, in integer numbers, between their lengths. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where would there be many people sitting in chair and listening to religious speech? Choices:  A: auditorium B: office C: synagogue D: confession E: church<n>Output:		 A<n><n>####  Expected Result<n>: *a and c*<n><n>```<n> <n>--- Day 16 ---<n>```<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:What is a mobile launching platform found in the ocean? Choices:  A: launch pad B: circus C: aircraft carrier D: large open area E: space station<n>Output:		 B<n>[Solution from MIT OpenCourseware 18.641 Discrete Mathematics Spring 2010](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/mathematics/18-641-discrete-mathematics-spring-2010/readings/MIT18_641S04_Syllabus.pdf)<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the two (2) multi part questions below.<n><n>### Question 1:<n><n>1. 	Write a program to determine the maximum number of toys a person can buy with 0, $1, $2 or more. The input will be a single (int) value.<n>2. 	Write a recursive algorithm to create the tree-structured expression.<n>	(a).	If the expression is true, the left- and right-hand sides of the expression must be true.<n>		(I).	(a)	If left and right are expressions, or an expression and a variable, the program  should recursively evaluate left and right.<n>		(b)	Evaluate the left and right hand expressions recursively if either is an expression or a statement containing an expression.<n>		(c)	If both values are expressions, evaluate recursively both left and right for both the left and right hand side of the expression as a true boolean value.<n>	(b).	If the expression  is  false, the left- and  right-hand sides of  the expression  must  be false.<n>#### Example:<n>`1   -   false -  false -  false - false -  false -  1 - - false <n>- false 1 -  true - false - true  - false - false   false  <n>- false  -  true -  true - false   false -   true - false <n><n>Answer: False`<n>### Question 2:<n><n>1.	Write a recursive function to check if a given string is a palindrome or not<n>2.	Write a recursive recursive function that takes a string and an integer and returns the sub string of that string that is the rest of the string after removing first that many characters so that the last character remains<n>3.	Write a function to read a string with any character and print the first 300 characters<n>

How many of the 36 people in the study have the disease?<n>2. The rate of diagnosis for those 36 people is 3/4. If the disease rates 10/1000, what percentage of 30-year-olds should be diagnosed with the disease?<n><n>Solution<n><n>The probability to have the disease is:<n><n>P = 3/4 x 1/1000 x 30 <n><n>P = 0.00075<n><n>We want to calculate the probability to be diagnosed as:<n><n>P’ = 10/12<n><n>Similar cases are as follows:<n><n>3. If 10/13 people are diagnosed with the disease in a community of a million people, what is the chance of a randomly-selected person to be diagnosed with the disorder?<n><n>Solution:<n><n>10/13 x 1/20th = 13

There is a bakery, a market, a farmer's market and a specialty grocery store.  I will go to the specialty grocery first. If I am not satisfied, then I will go to the farmer's market. If I am very satisfied I will go to the market. Finally if I  am utterly satisfied I will go to bakery. In all the stores, each item costs $4 less than one at the previous store.<n><n>**Eg:**<n><n>If I am very satisfied, but not satisfied enough, then I will go only from the market to bakery because the price difference is 4$ which is a great difference. But, if I am satisfied enough, I will go from farmer's market to market because the price difference is only $3 which is not a big deal.<n><n>#### Code:<n><n>def solution(n, m): <n>    res = 0<n>    answer = [1,1,1,3,2]<n>    s,m = 0,1<n>    curr = s<n>    for i in range(5):<n>        if n == i: return res<n>        if m < (i+curr):<n>            res = res+

How much is the cost of 15 eggs?<n>Output: 64.99 cents<n><n># Solution: <n>```<n>    def solution(self, s, d):<n>        from math import ceil, pow<n><n>        '''<n>        If we have a number 'd' that is already an integer, we could write "int(d)" and get the same thing as d but a python builtin. But here, that does not work. So we make our own function.<n>        '''<n>        def int_(f):<n>            return int([f]*5/4)<n>        d = int_(d)<n><n>        # This can be simplified<n>        if d < s:<n>            return 0<n>        elif d == s:<n>            return d<n>        result = 0<n>        while True:<n>            if d >= s*10:<n>                d = int(d/10)<n>                s += 1<n>            else:<n>                result += d<n>                d = int(-d)<n>            if d < s: break <n>        return result<n>```<n># Notes:<n><n>### Question:Input: This is a string. The function takes two strings and returns the smallest and largest string of those input strings.<n><n>### Question Input: Find the number of values from the string which are the same. If none is the same, return 0. Example: "Alice was here" should equal 0.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Solution:<n>```<n>    def is_same_number(num1, num2):<n>        s1 = str(num1)<n>        s2 = str(num2)<n>        <n>        for i in s1:<n>            if i not in s2:<n>                return 1<n>            else pass<n>                        <n>        return 0<n>```<n><n><n>### Question : Input: Use the given strings to tell if a triangle can be made<n><n>Solution: <n>```<n>'''<n><n>        a = 3<n><n>        def is_pythagorean(s):<n>            h1 = 1.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. Choices:  A: tide pool B: beach sand C: tidepools D: current E: cooking pot<n>Output:		B<n>######################################################################################<n>#Author:Shengyu_Zhuang<n>#Github: https://github.com/syZhuang<n>#Email:szzhuang@gmail.com<n>###########################################################################<n>"""<n>Created on Jun 25, 2017<n>@author: Shengyu_ZHUANG<n>"""<n><n><n>class Solution:<n>    def countSquares(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:<n>        count = 0<n>        for n in nums:<n>            if n == 0:<n>                break<n>            count += n<n>        return count<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    solu = Solution()<n>    nums = [2,3,4,5,6].copy()<n>    print(solu.countSquares(nums))<n>    # [2, 3, 4, 5, 6] -> 3<n>

Choices:  American English British English Cantonese Mandarin Spanish French Russian<n>Output: A<n>## Solution:<n><n>def read_input(string)<n>  input = nil<n>  return input if string.empty?<n>  input = string.split(" ", 4).map(&:to_i)<n>end<n><n>def part_i(input)<n>  n_dogs = 0<n>  input.each do |item|<n>    if item == 0<n>      break<n>    else<n>      n_dogs += item<n>    end<n>  end<n>  n_dobs_left = 20 - n_dogs<n>  return n_dogs, n_dobs_right + n_dogs < 5? n_dogs + 1 : 0<n>end<n><n>def read_statement<n>  data<n>end<n><n>def process<n>  process_statement(read_statement)<n>end<n><n>process<n><n>def process_statement(statement)<n>  parts = statement.split(" is equal to ")<n>  if parts.length > 1<n>    statement = statement.replace("is equal to ", "")<n>    parts.map { |part| part.strip }.each do |val|<n>      val = val.strip<n>      unless part_i(val[1..-1]).nil?<n>        return part_i(val)<n>      end<n>    end<n>  else<n>    return 0<n>  end<n>  unless parts.size > 1<n>    puts 'Invalid input'<n>    exit<n>  end<n>  parts.map { |p| p.strip }.each_with_index do |data, i|<n>    unless (data.is_a? Integer)<n>      puts "Not an Integer"<n>      exit<n>    end<n>    if i + 1 == parts.size<n>      return data<n>    end<n>  }<n>end<n><n># read_statement.flatten.slice(1..-1).each_with_index(0) { |elem, index| elem.is_a?(Integer) && print index && elem}<n>## 7<n><n>## 6<n><n><n>## 5<n><n><n>## 4<n>

So now if Dr. Banks gives away (330-45+45+12) for the last two months which would be equal to 73 toothbrush. so, we find there are remaining 257 number of toothbrands after he gives these away. So the answer should be approximately 257.<n>

Choices: A: 29 B: 2 C: 60 D: 71 E: 4<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: There are 20 bananas in a bunch. There are 16 fewer bananas in the bunch than there are apples in a box. Choices: A. 1 B. 2 C. 3 D. 4 E. 5<n>Output: 2<n><n>## Solution:<n>- Write an expression that uses the input parameters and outputs the expected result of that expression.<n>- Write a method to compute expressions and expected results.<n>- Then write a method to evaluate input parameters and output the results of those expression.<n><n>```python<n><n>def evaluate(A,B):#outputs the answer to a mathematical expressions.<n>	#input parameters to this method are: expressions and answers to these expressions.<n>	<n>	A1=A[0] #assigns expressions to the index 0<n>	#A[1] assign a value to the index 1.<n>	#A[n] assign a value to each index<n>	#print(type(A))<n>	<n>	temp=0<n>	#calculations in for loops iterate each time<n>	for x in range(0,len(A)):<n>		if A[x]==int(temp):<n>			return(A[x])<n>		else:<n>			temp=int(A[x])*int(B[x])<n>	<n>	<n><n>#evaluate(30/6, 2)<n><n>#evaluate("30/6",3)<n><n>#evaluated arguments<n><n>A=[6,30,4]<n>B=[6,3,4]<n>result

Choices:  A: serve food B: eat C: set table D: serve meal E: present bill<n>Output:		2019-07-25 | 답변 없음 | A<n><n><n>---<n><n>### 코드:<n>```python<n>def count(num):<n>    return num%10<n><n>def main():<n>    n = int(input())<n>    s,e = list(range(n, -1, -1))<n>    s.sort()<n>    e.sort(reverse=True)<n>    diff = len(e) - len(s)<n>    if e == s:<n>        return sum(count(x) for x in set(e))<n>    else:<n>        return diff<n><n>result = print(main()) * 9<n>```<n><n><n>---<n>

If he wishes to give one dozen balls for 1/2 the remaining, how many balls does he have left?<n>Output: 18<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>I used the brute force method to solve these questions:<n><n>I created a recursive method `doubleHelper()` that doubles its input.<n>Then, i created the method `divideHelper(int a, int b, int c)` that divides its input into the value of `b`.<n>I then created `answerHelper()` that takes the output of both `doubleHelper()` and `divideHelper(x, b, c)`, where `b` is the int that should be divided by `c`.<n>Finally, I created `main()` that calls `answerHelper()` to answer the questions.<n><n>### Code:<n>```<n>     public double doubleHelper (){<n>        if(value == 1)<n>            return 2;<n>            return value * 2;<n>        }<n>```<n><n>    public int divideHelper(int a,int b,int c) {<n>        int output = 0;<n><n>        if(b > 0){<n>            int output = a / b;<n>            if(output%c <= 0){<n>                output = output + 1;<n>                return output/c;<n>            }<n><n><n><n>        }<n><n>        return output;<n><n>    }<n><n>    public int answerHelper(int value){<n><n>        double helper1 =doubleHelper(value);<n>        int helper2= divideHelper(value, 2, 5);<n><n>        return helper1 + helper2;<n><n>    }

Choices:  A: ruined B: clean clothes C: sadness D: attractive appearance E: look better<n>Output:		C<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the questions below to test your understanding of the previous concepts and readiness for the next ones<n><n>**Question:**How many elements are present in the list `[1, 2, 3]`, what is the output when the elements are taken one-by-one in the list?<n><n>**Answer:** The output of the list is a single element. This will be achieved in Python using `list` method `pop()`<n><n>**Notes to Remember:**<n>- `pop()` returns the element immediately taken out of the list. It is generally used to remove the last elements from the list in a loop.<n>- Since the element is in an array, the `pop()` method can be used to delete that element from the list.<n>- It is a `mutable` list method.<n>- The new pop method takes one argument which is the `index of the element.`<n>- It is an element function, which returns the value of the function evaluated on the passed element.<n>- If the index is not passed, it will return the last element from the list. <n>  - `If the list is empty, then it will raise and error.`<n>- To remove all the elements of the list using pop, call the pop function from the second position to the last position of the list.<n><n><n>**Question: What is the output of [1, 2, [3, 4], [5, 6], 7]?**<n><n>**Answer: The list is of length 5 and can be written as `list1=[1,2,3,4,5]`. So, the result is `[1,2,3]`. Here, index 4 and 5 of list 1 gets replaced by the elements of array `[3,4].`  When index 4 is in `list1`, which element from `[3,4]` is to be taken? Now, the elements of array are `[3,4]`. Index `[5,6]` will take elements `[5,6]` from `[3,4]`.<n><n>**Question: Explain the output of `[1, 2]` in Python.**<n>**Answer:** We have two indexes, `[1,2]` in the list. Index one returns an element `1` and index `2`, it will return an element from `[2]`. So, `[1,2]=[1,2].

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where will a bullet projectile be found during a war? Choices:  A: battle field B: museum C: weapon D: canon E: tornado<n>Output:		A<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>####  Question 1<n><n>To solve this question, we need to use the idea of distributive law:<n><n>```python<n>n * (5 - (100-n)/3) = 90    # distributive laws<n>10 * (5 - (20-5)/3)       # equivalent to<n>50 - 10 * 5   <n><n>10 * (4 - (25-10)/3)<n>10 * 15/3<n><n>10 * 5    <n>```<n><n>Since, we know the difference between the Dobermans and the Schnauzers should be the same as in a question, `5/3 = 1.66\6` to keep it simple, to be `15/3` there should be 33 dogs total in the shelter. So the Schnauzrs should be `(100-20)/3 = 6\3` which is 20 dogs.<n><n>```python<n>import math<n><n>def solute_question1(n):<n>    solution=math.pow(3,3)*33<n>    if(n=0):<n>        return solution-33<n>    else:<n>        return abs(n)/3-solution<n>for i in range(100):<n>    for j in range(20):<n>        print(i,(solute_question1(i)))<n>```<n><n>#### Question 2<n><n>To solve this, the easiest way is to convert the months to days and then count each days from `0` until `31`. You need to use the `while-loop` and `range` to do it.<n><n>```python <n>import math<n><n>months_to_day = { 13. : 31, 2. : 29 , 4. : 30 }<n><n>def solute2(n):<n>        month_list = [0,31,31,30,30,31]<n>        counter=0<n>        while(counter<month_list[0]+1):<n>                if(counter == n):<n>                    print(month_list[0])<n>                    n = 1<n>                else:<n> <n>                        counter += 1  <n>

Choices:  A: backpack B: dog show C: chinese food D: french E: good hands<n>Output:		chinese food<n><n><n># Import Python libraries<n>from dataclasses import unique, dataclass<n>from functools import reduce, partial<n>from operator import mul, add, or_, and_<n>from decimal import Decimal<n>from typing import List<n><n>@dataclass<n>class Solution:<n>    def getLuckyIndex(self, nums: List[int], j: int) -> int:<n>        n = len()<n>        j*=n<n>        sum = 0<n>        for i, num in enumerate(nums):<n>            if i!= j:<n>                sum += num<n>            else:<n>                return sum<n><n><n>def getLuckyIndexSolution(nums: List[int]) -> int:<n>    nums = unique(nums)<n>    max_j = len(nums) - 1<n>    return getLuckyIndex(nums, max_j)<n><n>def getLuckIndexSolution(num_list: List[int])->int:<n>    num = [i for i in range(1,len(num_list)) if<n>           (num_list[i-1] + num_list[i]) % 2 == 0]<n>    return num.index(max(num))<n>    max_num = max(num_list)<n>    if max_num % 2 == 1:<n>        return num_list.index(max_num - 1)<n>    else:<n>        return num.index(int((2 * (max_num))))<n>    return num_list.pop() <n><n>def getLickyIndex(nums: int, j: int) -> tuple:<n>    j = j * nums<n>    if sum(nums) == 16:<n>        return (nums, j)<n>    else: <n>      return None<n><n>def solve():<n>    assert 1 == reduce(or_, [getLickyIndex(3, j)<n>        for j in range(1, 10)])<n>    assert 16 == solve(getLuckyIndex(3,j) <n>                for j in range(2, 10))<n><n>solve()

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Where can you eat fruit on a red bridge? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: engineering school C: san francisco D: tree E: market<n>Output:		E<n><n>Output: A<n><n>Input: One hundred and something men, all named John, went into a bar.  John the first had red hair. John the second had blond hair. One hundred and thirty-five had hair?<n>Output: John the 134th had to comb the hair on his head and on the sides of his face.<n><n>```python<n>a = 3<n>b = 5<n>c = float((a + b) / 2)<n>d = abs(a * b)<n>if a == b:<n>    print('The answer is',c)<n>else:<n>    print('It is a ',d)<n>```<n><n>### Your Solution<n><n>```python<n>if a == b and c == (a+b)/2 and d == abs((a*b)):<n>    print(c)<n>elif a>b and c == (a-b)/2:<n>    print(c )<n>else:<n>    a = int(raw_input())<n>    b = int(raw_next_number())<n>    c = (a+b)/float(2)<n>    d = abs((c*a) * (c*b))<n>    #print(c)<n>    print((-1 if a > b else 1))<n>```<n>

There are $N$ operations to perform on $S_1$:<n>* For each $I \in S_1$, $I$ is multiplied by 3.<n>* $s_1$ and $s_2$ are interchanged. ($s_1 + s_2 = x$.)<n>* Every two elements in this sequence are reversed. ($s_1, s_2, s_3 = x$)<n>If you apply these operations and get the same sequence, are we dealing with duplicate elements in the sequence $S_1$?<n><n>**Answer:** In this case: the sequence $S_2$ will have identical elements. I.e. If one $j$ is present in $S_1, S_2$, then so is exactly one $j$ in $S$ for any $1 \leq i \leq N-1$.<n><n>**Question #2:** How can you show that your answer to the first question is correct?<n><n>**Answer: **We do not use a proof by contradiction. Instead, we are considering different element in the sequence $S$, and showing that a certain operation (the multiplication by 3, or the reversal of 2 elements etc.) can not lead to having the same elements in consecutive positions. We show: if for some choice of indices (in the sequence of $N$ operations to be performed on $S$), the operation $(s_{i-1}, s_{i}, s_{i+1}) = e$, i.e. they are replaced by a certain element $\ e$, then we obtain the same elements after applying any of the other operations with the same indices $i$.<n><n> <n><n>#### Instructions:Answer all the following MCQ Questions.<n><n>**Ques #1**: You have a sequence of elements, and you do a certain operation on each element. You find out that you can continue performing the operation without any restrictions. In other words, there will be no restriction, for example: the same 2 operations will not be repeated. How can you prove that there is an element in the sequence that is repeated twice? <n><n>**Answer**: We can prove this by using mathematical induction. If $A_1 =

Choices: Choice: A: 4 B: 5<n>Output:<n><n>#### 3.21 Hanging Questions<n>A hanging question is a question that asks for the answer in the form of a boolean value (0 or 1). The answer is either yes or no. When the computer is given the problem, it will try to find a logical yes or no and output it.<n>An example of a hanging question is: Is the computer turned on? Choice: true, false  Note: Boolean values are either true, false, on or off, yes or no.<n>Output: True or false.<n>Notice that the question is answered either yes or no. The boolean true will be either a True, or a yes. The boolean false will be either False, or no.  Remember that this can happen in a computer program you write.<n>A Hanging question does have a second form:<n><n>##### A. True, False or Can't Decide?<n>Input: There are 119 pizzas in Pizza Hut.  Input: Is the pizza better than the rest?<n>Output: True or False.<n><n>#### B. <n>Input: Your favorite color is a secret...<n>Output: Yes or No<n><n>#### C:<n>Input: Your favorite food is a secret...<n><n>**Pizza or sushi?*<n><n>Input: Pizza sushi<n><n>#### D:<n>Input: How old is it? <n>Output: Age?<n><n>#### E:<n>**Input: <n>What time is it?**<n><n>

How many beers will the bartender sell when he has two specials?<n>Output: 76<n><n>-Note: Above problems has been written by [Patrick](https://github.com/patricksy)<n>### Solution<n><n>In this problem, I think we just need to solve the order of how we add those values.  <n>### Solution1 <n>If we add each number by each other, the answer would be 90:<n>```C#<n>int tempDob = 5; // tempDob variable will contain sum of Dob to Do to Schnauzers <n>int tempSch = 20; // tempSch variable would contain sum of Do to Schnauzer<n>int result = 90;     // result variable will hold sum of Dob to Dob and Dob to Schnauzer to Schnauzsers and Schnauz<n>          // Dob + (Do*3) - (Do*3) = Dob = 5 + 15 - 15 = 3   <n>          // Do + (Dob*3) - (Dob*3)- (Do*3) + (Dob*5) - (Do*5) = 53 <n>int dobToDo = dobToDo*3;<n>int dobToSchn = dobToSchn*3;<n>int doToDo = doToDo*5;<n>int doToSchn = doToSchn*5;<n>int resultDob = dobToDo+dobToSchn;<n>```<n>### Solution 2 <n>I think we could just use `do` variable instead, it will result the same answer, it will be like this:<n>```C# <n>int tempDob;<n>int tempSch;<n>int result;<n>int Do;<n>int DoToDo;<n>int DoToSchn

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Eating breakfast with a large family leads to a pile of what in the sink? Choices:  A: fullness B: underwear C: bad breath D: better day E: dirty dishes<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:When your boss tells you to do a project that will take you a month, you say you could do it in half that time. He’s excited when he learns you only need 1 week to complete the project.How long did it actually take you to complete the project in reality?<n>Output:2 weeks<n>#### Note<n>*If there is more than one solution, then your answer must be the answer with the highest accuracy.<n><n>**********************************************\<n><n># Solution Description<n>There are several problems that seem to be overlapping. First, you have a nested loop. You can see this pattern. After several trial and error, i realized i can solve this problem in `O(N^2)` by building a list. There are `n^2` possibility but the nested condition is `n` which we cant just avoid. In the list, we will store the number of children in each parent (this can be redefined using a counter for better performance) and since there is no nesting anymore, this can be done in `O(n)` time.<n><n>Also note that the nested condition is `5` and not just `1` for the solution in the book. As always. This is why you need to be attentive to the condition.<n><n># Results<n><n>|Method| Time Complexity | Time Taken |<n>|-----|:----------------:|:-----------:|<n>| List | O(n^2) 🧐 | 5 🧐  |<n>| List | O(|n|)  🧐 🧐  🧐 |         |

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Choices:  A: band B: music room C: college D: university E: house<n>Output:		Music room<n><n>Input:A man with a dog and a dog with a man<n>Output:M<n><n>Input:Given a list of numbers, calculate the last position index of the first duplicate number.<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input:Create new arrays of numbers (1,2,3,4,5) and (6,5,4,3,2) where the sum of the difference, i.e. first row - last is equal to the sum of the first row - (i.+1). For example (1,2,8) and (2,4,6).<n>Output: 2<n>'''<n><n>class Solution:<n>    '''<n>    @param S: A list of integers<n>    @return A list of integers<n>    <n>    '''<n>    def checkPairsSum2(self, nums):<n>        '''<n>        <n>        Args:<n>            nums(list): a list containing input numbers<n>        Return:<n>            A sorted list containing each integers in pairs where their sum is equal to the number after nums.<n>        Example:<n>            Given nums = [4, 34, 84],<n>            Return [1, 12, 32, 83]<n>        '''<n>         i = 1<n>         m = len(nums)<n>         tempArray = []<n><n>        for i in range(2,m):<n>            while len(tempArray) <= i:<n>                tempArray.append(nums[i])<n><n>         for j in range(1,i):  <n>              if(nums[j]!= nums[j-1]):<n>                   break <n>              tempArray.append(i+1)<n>         return sorted(tempArray)<n>'''<n>Solution.checkPairsSum2([4,34,84]) == [(1,12),(32,83)]<n>'''<n><n>import timeit<n>for t in range(100):<n>    start = timeit.Timer( Solution.checkPairsSum, "(a, b)",{"a":(i,i+1)})<n>    end = timeit.Timer("","end=")<n>    print(start.timeit("-a")[0]) # time taken <n>    print(end.timeit("-t"))<n>    '''<n><n>

(read as the letter n followed by an exclamation point) to mean 1 * 2 * 3 * 4 * 5 * … * n. So, for example, the value of n! is 1 * 2, since 1 * 2 is the sum of all the natural numbers less than 2 – namely 1 plus 2. There is a rule for n! that works for any positive integer n (it might be called a “formula”). You have to use the “factorial” button, which is the button with a squiggly symbol above it (in most apps just hit your parenthesis button). The formula is: n! = n * (n - 1) *
